{"cursor":"13107","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Julius Robert von Mayer |image =Julius Robert Mayer\nvon Friedrich Berrer.jpg |image_size = |caption = Julius Robert von Mayer\n|birth_date = November 25, 1814 |birth_place = Heilbronn |death_date =\n|death_place = Heilbronn |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = Germany\n|ethnicity = |field = Physics |work_institutions = |alma_mater = University of\nTÃ¼bingen |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = First law of\nthermodynamics |author_abbrev_bot =|author_abbrev_zoo = |influences =\n|influenced = William Thomson |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }}\n\n'Julius Robert von Mayer' (November 25, 1814 â March 20, 1878) was a German\nphysician and physicist and one of the founders of thermodynamics. He is best\nknown for enunciating in 1841 one of the original statements of the conservation\nof energy or what is now known as one of the first versions of the first law of\nthermodynamics, namely that \"energy can be neither created nor\ndestroyed\". Mayer, Robert (1841). Paper: 'Remarks on the Forces of Nature\";\nas quoted in: Lehninger, A. (1971). Bioenergetics - the Molecular Basis of\nBiological Energy Transformations, 2nd. Ed. London: The Benjamin/Cummings\nPublishing Company. 30+ Variations of the 1st Law of Thermodynamics -\nIoHT Publications. In 1842, Mayer described the vital chemical process now\nreferred to as oxidation as the primary source of energy for any living\ncreature. His achievements were overlooked and priority for the discovery of the\n[[mechanical equivalent of heat]] was attributed to James Joule in the following\nyear. He also proposed that plants convert light into chemical energy.\n","linknr":302,"url":"Mayer's_Relation","recorded":1374779691,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Julius_von_Mayer&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Julius_von_Mayer&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php",